  "text": "As discussed above, hardening by cooling would change relative longitudinal strain rates in different rheological domains, because a partially molten material would accommodate more easily the deformation [CITATION_1] . At this time, extensional motion along the earlier foliation planes and extensional ductile shear zones could have been nucleated in order to maintain material compatibility between the oblique mov- ing slices during extrusion and oblique convergence. The fi nite structure resembles a triangle zone in cross-sections typical of extrusion tectonics (see [CITATION_2] (Figs. 5b 1 and 6 b) . The footwall obliquely extrudes toward the SSW and was uplifted during transpression and parallel motion (see inlet in Fig. 5b ).",
